<h2>FAQ</h2>
<h3>What is ScholarSphere?</h3>
<p>
Penn State's ScholarSphere is a research repository service collecting scholarly work from faculty, staff and students beginning in September 2012.  It is being developed and supported in a partnership of the University Libraries and Digital Library Technologies, a division of Information Technology Services.  It enables members of the Penn State community including faculty, staff, and students to increase the visibility of their research and to share their scholarly work more widely.
</p>
<p>
Researchers can actively manage stored versions of their research and preserve it, ensuring its longevity over time for future generations of scholars to find, use, and build on. A trusted institutional service, ScholarSphere has safeguards in place for keeping private research secure and unchanged over time . The service allows the depositor to set the level of access possible by others.
</p>
<p>
Questions about ScholarSphere? Contact the project team: DLT-GAMMA-PROJECT@lists.psu.edu [this will change as we get helps in place]
</p>

<h3>How would I use it?</h3>
<p>
<strong>As a contributor</strong>, since anyone in the Penn State community involved in the research process will be able to deposit scholarly materials there. These might include project results, numeric data, videos, student theses and capstone projects, and other types of digital formats.
</p>
<p>
<strong>As a source of scholarly information</strong>, since it will have access to the work (text data, media, etc.) that other Penn State researchers contribute.
</p>

<h3>Why should I use ScholarSphere?</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Visibility for your research contributions.</strong>  Researchers can make digitized materials available easily for others to locate, setting a range of retrieval options from full access to just an indication that particular data exists.</li>
  <li><strong>Authoritative way to manage materials you submit.</strong>  Each item will be assigned an individual persistent identifier (“address”) so that it can be cited and retrieved, prior versions are accessible for editing, many formats are accepted, access level is set by the contributor.</li>
  <li><strong>Long term storage and preservation.</strong>   You will participate in a program that supports preservation and access over time. Meet the data management plan requirements mandated by grant funding agencies. </li>
</ul>

<h2>For Contributors To ScholarSphere</h2>
<h3>What can I do with ScholarSphere?</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Store your files</li>
  <li>Assign access rights - publicly downloadable, editable or
  downloadable by specified users or groups, or restricted to yourself</li>
  <li>Search, browse and view your files as well as other researchers’ public and shared files</li>
  <li>Identify and cite files using persistent, short URLs</li>
  <li>Add new versions of your files, see previous versions, and revert to a past version</li>
  <li>Tag files with metadata for increased discovery</li>
  <li>Export metadata to citation managers, e.g. Zotero or RefWorks</li>
  <li>Share your files with Penn State users or groups </li>
  <li>Verify that your files have not changed over time </li>
</ul>

